  "text": "Role of N-Terminal Sequence and Proteasomal Degradation in Expression of RGS Proteins. Given the known role of proteasomal degradation of RGS4 and RGS5 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , we explored proteasomal degradation of the other RGS proteins by inhibiting the proteasome with MG-132 as described previously [CITATION_4] . Inhibition of proteasome activity by MG-132 pretreatment (20 M; 4 h) caused a 3-fold increase in expression of RGS2 (Fig. 4 , A and B; P Ͻ 0.001), 20-fold increase for RGS4 (Fig. 4 , C and D; P Ͻ 0.001), and 5-fold increase for RGS5 (Fig. 4 , E and F; P Ͻ 0.05) and RGS8 (Fig. 4 , G and H; P Ͻ 0.001). Thus, RGS4 is strongly modulated by proteasomal inhibition, whereas effects on RGS2, -5, and -8 are more modest.",
